According to ''[[MicroScope]]'', the ZX Spectrum version of ''Light Force'' debuted at number two in the UK sales charts, behind [[Paperboy (video game)|''Paperboy'']].<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Your Sinclair]]|title=Hit List|page=14|date=January 1987|issue=13|url=https://archive.org/stream/YourSinclair37Jan89/YourSinclair/YourSinclair13-Jan87#page/n15/mode/2up/}}</ref> It dropped down to number three the following week.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=23–29 October 1986|title=Charts|url=https://archive.org/details/popular-computing-weekly-1986-10-23/page/n17/mode/2up|magazine=[[Popular Computing Weekly]]|issue=43|page=19}}</ref> All three versions of the game received positive reviews from video game critics. Graham Taylor for ''[[Sinclair User]]'' called it "the ultimate blaster" and "essential purchase".<ref name="Sinclair User Review">{{cite magazine|title=Lightforce Review|magazine=[[Sinclair User]]|last=Taylor|first=Graham|issue=55|pages=32–33|date=October 1986|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-055/SinclairUser_055_Oct_1986#page/n31/mode/2up}}</ref> One reviewer for ''[[Amtix]]'' considered it to be one of the best shoot 'em ups for the Amstrad.<ref name=Amtix/> [[Crash (magazine)|''Crash'']] praised its graphics, calling it the best he has seen on a Spectrum shoot 'em up.<ref name="Crash Review"/> [[Computer and Video Games]]{{'}} Tim Metcalfe positively compared it to ''[[Galaxian]]''.<ref name=CVG/> ''[[Zzap!64]]'' said that the title was appropriate for fans of scrolling shooter genre.<ref name=ZZap/>

The game won the award for best graphics of the year according to the readers of ''Crash'', and was nominated in the "Best Shoot 'em up" and "State of the Art award" categories.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]|title=The 1986 Crash Readers' Awards|page=35|issue=38|date=March 1987|url=https://archive.org/stream/crash-magazine-38/Crash_38_Mar_1987#page/n34/mode/1up}}</ref> In 1991, ''Crash'' placed it 82nd in their list of the top 100 games for the Spectrum.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]|title=Top 100 Speccy Games!|page=40|issue=91|date=August 1991|url=https://archive.org/details/Crash_No._91_1991-08_Newsfield_GB/page/n37}}</ref> The Spectrum version was rated number 26 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]]'' "Official Top 100 Games of All Time" list.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Let the People Decide! The Results!|magazine=[[Your Sinclair]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|page=11|issue=93|date=September 1993|url=https://archive.org/stream/your-sinclair-93/YourSinclair_93_Sep_1993#page/n57/mode/2up}}</ref>

